Ôªø# Miles 9.3b vs 9.3v: idle stream feeding ‚Äî evidence report

Honoring **CONSULT-35v-AXIOMS.md** (L1‚ÄìL5 locked; ordinal/relink framing banned).

---

## (a) What the 9.3b docs say drives an idle stream

The decompiled CHM is **9.3b only** (`changelog.html:50` ‚Äî *"This documentation is for Miles version 9.3b"*). There is **no 9.3v help or changelog on disk**.

### Default model: background auto-service via a secondary thread

**`AIL_open_stream` discussion** (`AIL_open_stream.html:133‚Äì141`):

> *"Streams are automatically serviced in the background by default. You can service the buffers manually with the `AIL_service_stream` and `AIL_auto_service_stream` functions."*

> *"This function doesn't actually load any of the streaming buffers ‚Äî the only routine in the streaming API that performs the file reading is `AIL_service_stream`."*

(Initial open still does a synchronous header read ‚Äî consistent with axiom in `CONSULT-35v-AXIOMS.md:51‚Äì52`.)

**`AIL_auto_service_stream` discussion** (`AIL_auto_service_stream.html:19‚Äì20, 68‚Äì70, 95‚Äì99`):

> *"turns auto-servicing on or off for a stream handle (it's turned on by default)."*

> *"On most platforms, auto-streaming is accomplished with a secondary thread."*

> *"The only real reason you should ever have to turn off auto-streaming is if you want exact control of when file reading should take place."*

### Who calls the read callback

**`AIL_set_file_callbacks` discussion** (`AIL_set_file_callbacks.html:112‚Äì113`):

> *"On most platforms, these functions can be called from a background thread. So, you must make sure you IO callbacks are thread-safe."*

**Packed-file FAQ** (`How_do_I_access_files_from_a_big_packed_file_.html:48`):

> *"Miles uses synchronous IO from a background thread to do its IO."*

**`AIL_service_stream` discussion** (`AIL_service_stream.html:94‚Äì95`):

> *"If you are having trouble with streams skipping, you can try sprinkling calls to this function to give the background IO thread a little extra breathing room."*

### IO thread + foreground starvation fallback

**`AIL_IO_thread_handle` discussion** (`AIL_IO_thread_handle.html:19‚Äì20, 59‚Äì60, 78‚Äì79`):

> *"retrieves the platform specific thread handle that Miles uses for it's IO reading."*

**`AIL_serve` description + discussion** (`AIL_serve.html:19‚Äì20, 70‚Äì71, 80‚Äì81`):

> *"provides periodic foreground service to the Miles Sound System to avoid 'starvation' during periods when the application does not yield control frequently."*

> *"This function can be used to manually pump the Miles background processing - it's useful if the background thread is liable to become starved. It's normally only called in unusual situations‚Ä¶"*

**Windows CPU sharing** (`Sharing_the_CPU_under_Windows.html:52‚Äì56`):

> *"Under Windows, Miles does most of its work in a background thread. This means that Miles usually does its work without you even having to worry about it."*

> *"The only time you may need to specifically give Miles CPU time is if the system thread scheduler starts performing badly and the background Miles thread starves."*

### Doc summary (idle / low-I/O)

| Mechanism | Doc claim |
|---|---|
| **Default idle feeder** | Secondary thread auto-services streams (`AIL_auto_service_stream`, ON by default) |
| **Actual file reads** | Only `AIL_service_stream` reads into stream buffers (after open's initial chunk) |
| **Read callback thread** | File callbacks may be invoked from the background/IO thread |
| **Manual override** | `AIL_service_stream` / `AIL_serve` for explicit control or starvation recovery |
| **Dedicated IO thread** | `AIL_IO_thread_handle` exposes the Miles IO thread |

The docs do **not** say idle feeding depends on application I/O load. They describe a **background thread that should run independently** of main-thread activity.

